actions -- the things that an object does; the functional characteristics of
	an object as opposed to its appearance or sound.
activity -- generic term for something for players to do in Habitat.
adventure -- a major class of activity, characterized by exploration and
	questing after treasure.
adventure master -- special type of privileged user empowered by us to
	manipulate the world in certain ways in order to make it fun for
	everybody else.
Anderson, Cathy -- Quantum person in charge of Habitat project coordination in
	Virginia.
Arnold, Steve -- head of Lucasfilm Games Division.
Avatar -- the humanoid character that a player controls in Habitat.
behavior code -- software on either the host or the C64 to implement an
	objects actions (i.e., to make it do whatever it does).
body sprayer -- a type of object that changes the color or pattern of parts
	of an Avatar's body (since Avatars don't have clothes).
book -- a type of object that carries text readable by players.
bureaucrat-in-a-box -- a type of Oracle that provides communication with
	system operators.
C64 -- common abbreviation for Commodore 64.
c -- programming language on Unix systems used to create most of the LFL
	utilities.
capacity monitor -- set of routines on the host computer that lets it know if
	the C64 is about to run out of memory.
Case, Steve -- Quantum marketing guy.
cel -- fragment of imagery used in rendering animation on the C64.
Change-O-Matic -- a type of object that changes the color of pattern of
	permanent objects in an Avatar's turf.
Commodore 64 -- cheap, mass market computer that Habitat runs on.
container -- any object that can hold other objects as part of its state
	information.
Control Video Corporation -- predecessor company to Quantum.
database -- in general any bunch of stuff stored on a computer; in our case
	the collection of files on the host that describes the Habitat world.
do -- one of the five essential verbs of the Habitat user interface; causes
	something to be done with an object (exactly what depends on what sort
	of object it is).
ESP -- means by which online Avatars can communicate over long distances.
Falstein, Noah -- LFL programmer involved in early Habitat concept
	development.
Farmer, Randy -- LFL programmer responsible for much of C64 Habitat code.
fastlink -- LFL development tool that connects a Sun workstation to the inside
	of a C64; consists of both custom hardware and custom software.
genesis -- utility on host that turns Riddle output into database entries.
get -- one of the five essential verbs of the Habitat user interface; causes
	Avatar to pick up an object.
ghost -- non-corporeal form of an Avatar; allows players to move around
	despite crowds and to gather in theaters and so on.
Ghu -- hypothetical host utility to manipulate the world; acronym for God's
	Handy Utility.
Gilbert, Ron -- LFL programmer who coded first version of C64 database
	routines.
go -- one of the five essential verbs of the Habitat user interface; causes
	Avatar to move around.
Grigg, Chris -- LFL contractor who created C64 sound effects for Habitat.
Habitat -- this whole schmere.
Hall of Records -- a place in Habitat where we post the moral equivalent of
	high score tables.
head -- a type of object that rests on Avatar's shoulders to distinguish one
	from another.
host -- the Stratus computer in Virginia that coordinates the Habitat
	universe.
Hunter, Janet -- Quantum programmer who wrote the host system software for
	Habitat.
image disk -- one side of the C64 Habitat disk; contains images, sound effects
	and behavior code for all objects.
Kellner, Charlie -- LFL programmer who created the cel animation system on the
	C64 that Habitat uses.
Kimsey, Jim -- head honcho of Quantum.
Lucas, George -- he's just this guy, you know?
Lucasfilm Games Division -- part of Lucasfilm that does computer games and so
	on; folks bringing you Habitat.
Lucasfilm Ltd. -- a little known movie company in Marin.
Macklin, Ken -- artist who did many of the heads in Habitat.
Macross -- super-duper 6502 assembler in LFL develoment system.
magic -- general purpose mechanism for implementing random, idiosyncratic
	behaviors.
mail -- Habitat communications mechanism that lets one Avatar send a message
	to another, even if the recipient is not online.
message -- a transmission from C64 to host or vice versa that makes things
	happen in the world.
message protocol -- communications technique that lets us send messages back
	and forth.
Mohler, Nancy -- LFL person responsible for coordinating Habitat project in
	Marin.
Morningstar, Chip -- Habitat designer and project leader; LFL programmer.
Muddle -- LFL utility to generate C64 image disk.
object -- generic term for a thing in the Habitat world.
Oracle -- the omnipresent being who rules over Habitat.
Paterno, Mary -- LFL Games Division super secretary.
pawnshop -- object that converts other objects into tokens to recycle them.
People Connection -- Q-Link online chat facility.
pl1 -- cheezy programming language on the host.
player -- a Habitat subscriber; preferred term over user.
pockets -- where an Avatar keeps stuff; Avatars are marsupials (they have to
	be since they don't have clothes).
Populopolis -- Habitat's first town,
program disk -- one side of the C64 Habitat disk; contains the Habitat program
	itself.
put -- one of the five essential verbs of the Habitat user interface; causes
	Avatar to put things down.
Q-Link -- short for QuantumLink.
QuantumLink -- online service offered by Quantum.
realm -- a connected collection of regions created for some purpose.
recursion -- see recursion.
region -- a place in Habitat.
region editor -- LFL utility for creating regions.
region transition -- when an Avatar moves from one region to another; common
	cause of software bugs and performance problems.
regionproc -- main host program for Habitat.
reincarnation -- what happens when an Avatar dies.
Reno -- successor to region editor; standalone product for C64; so named
	because it's not quite as sleazy as Las Vegas.
Riddle -- LFL utility that generates data files for host that describe
	regions.
Serrif, Marc -- Quantum head techie.
Slur -- LFL utility that converts output of region editor so Riddle can read
	it; acronym for Stupid Little Utility for Riddle.
Smalltalk -- famous object-oriented programming language on which underlying
	Habitat system is based.
Stratus -- non-stop minicomputer based on redundant 68000s that is what the
	host runs on.
Sun -- 68000 based personal workstation that is primary LFL development
	system.
sysop -- short for system operator, a volunteer user who helps make things run
	in return for free system use.
talk -- one of the five essential verbs in the Habitat user interface; causes
	Avatars to communicate with each other face to face or to input text
	of any sort.
Telenet -- nationwide packet switching network that connects C64s to host.
TelePort -- mechanism of long-distance transport in Habitat.
token -- unit of money in Habitat.
True Names -- novel by Vernor Vinge that was large inspiration for Habitat.
trust fund -- where an Avatar gets his living expenses from.
Turf -- a region that an Avatar can call his own.
twiddle -- host utility to manually manipulate the database.
universe -- a collection of software and data for games like Habitat; Habitat
	is a universe.
Unix -- nifty operating system used on LFL development systems.
Vax -- DEC computer that is part of LFL development system.
vendroid -- Habitat vending machine.
Vinge, Vernor -- author of True Names.
VOS -- yucky operating system used on host computers.
Weekly Rant -- Habitat newspaper.
west pole -- the top of the world; where Habitat compasses point.
Wilmunder, Aric -- LFL programmer who wrote much of C64 Habitat code.
Winnick, Gary -- LFL artist who did almost all the object imagery and
	animation.
world -- a collection of realms represented by a database and a C64 image
	disk.
